        "messages": {
          "values": [
            {
              "content": "=You are a system that prepares documents for semantic search (RAG).\n\nYour task is to transform the input text into structured, high-quality chunks with metadata.\n\nOUTPUT FORMAT (STRICT):\nReturn a JSON array of objects. Each object must have:\n\n{\n  \"text\": \"string\",\n  \"source\": \"string\",\n  \"chunk_index\": number,\n  \"chunk_id\": string\n}\n\n- content: the cleaned and structured chunk text\n- source: a short identifier of the document (infer from context if not provided, otherwise use \"unknown\")\n- chunk_index: incremental index starting from 0\n- chunk_id: must be exactly source + \"_\" + chunk_index\n\nRULES:\n\n1. Each chunk must contain COMPLETE information.\n   - Minimum 3 sentences per chunk.\n   - Maximum ~150 words.\n\n2. DO NOT create small or meaningless chunks.\n   - Avoid titles alone.\n   - Avoid slogans, headers, or isolated phrases.\n\n3. NEVER create a chunk that is only a title, heading, label, or course name.\n   - If the text does not contain explanatory or actionable information, DISCARD it.\n\n4. Group related content into the same chunk.\n   - Merge paragraphs that belong to the same topic.\n\n5. Remove noise:\n   - Ignore branding, slogans, repeated headers, or irrelevant text.\n\n6. Preserve meaning:\n   - Do not lose important information.\n   - Keep explanations complete.\n\n7. Prefer fewer high-quality chunks over many small ones.\n\n8. Do NOT split sentences.\n   - Each chunk must start and end at natural sentence boundaries.\n\n9. Ignore:\n   - legal disclaimers\n   - institutional policies\n   - generic company descriptions\n\n10. Only include information that helps answer real user questions.\n\n11. Useful information includes:\n   - skills learned\n   - technologies used\n   - how something works\n   - steps, processes, or explanations\n   - outcomes, results, or capabilities\n\n12. Exclude vague or generic content such as:\n   - \"this course is constantly updated\"\n   - \"high quality experience\"\n   - \"designed for the modern world\"\n   - any generic marketing language\n\n13. Each chunk must be information-dense.\n   - Avoid chunks that are too general, repetitive, or low in informational value.\n\n14. Prioritize technical, educational, or explanatory content over descriptive or promotional text.\n\n15. If a chunk contains multiple distinct topics, split them into separate chunks.\n\n16. Avoid duplicate chunks:\n   - If multiple parts of the text repeat the same idea or phrase, include it only once.\n   - Do NOT generate semantically redundant chunks.\n\n17. Each chunk must provide UNIQUE value.\n   - If removing the chunk does not reduce the overall understanding, DISCARD it.\n\n18. Discard low-value text:\n   - Standalone titles\n   - Section names\n   - Navigation elements\n   - Repeated course names\n   - Any content shorter than 2 full sentences\n\n19. Metadata rules:\n   - chunk_index must increment sequentially (0, 1, 2, ...)\n   - source must be consistent across all chunks from the same input\n   - If a clear title, filename, or context exists, use it as source\n   - If not, use \"unknown\"\n   - chunk_id must follow: source + \"_\" + chunk_index\n\n20. Quality over quantity:\n   - It is better to return fewer chunks than to include low-quality ones.\n\n21. DO NOT include explanations outside the JSON.\n\nIMPORTANT:\n- Return ONLY valid JSON\n- Escape all quotes inside strings using \\\"\n- Do not include markdown (no ```json)\n\nReturn ONLY the JSON array.\n\nTEXT: {{ $json.markdown || $json.content }}"
            }
          ]
        },
        "builtInTools": {},
        "options": {}
